<task type="auto" tdd="true">
  <name>Task 1: Vendor a faithful line-for-line C# port of canonical ms-numpress linear + exact-vector tests</name>
  <files>ThermoRawFileParser/Writer/MzPeak/MSNumpress.cs, ThermoRawFileParser/ThermoRawFileParserTest/MzPeakChunkTests.cs</files>
  <behavior>
    AUTHORITY: the port is a FAITHFUL LINE-FOR-LINE port of the CANONICAL ms-numpress reference source
    (C++ MSNumpress.cpp / Java MSNumpress.java) for optimalLinearFixedPoint, encodeInt, decodeInt, encodeLinear,
    decodeLinear, encodeFixedPoint, decodeFixedPoint. Port from the REFERENCE SOURCE, NOT from any prose summary.
    The prose in RESEARCH-port.md section 1 mis-describes the algorithm (it says least-squares slope and 5-byte
    values / continuation-varint nibbles) — that prose is WRONG and MUST be ignored. The canonical facts below
    are authoritative.

    - OptimalLinearFixedPoint(double[]) is MAX-VALUE based (NOT least-squares): seed maxDouble = max(data[0],data[1]);
      for i>=2, extrapol = data[i-1] + (data[i-1]-data[i-2]), diff = data[i]-extrapol,
      maxDouble = max(maxDouble, ceil(abs(diff)+1)); return floor(0x7FFFFFFF / maxDouble).
      dataSize==0 -> 0; dataSize==1 -> floor(0x7FFFFFFF / data[0]).
    - EncodeLinear(double[], double fp): bytes 0-7 = fp as a BIG-ENDIAN IEEE-754 double (encodeFixedPoint);
      then data[0] and data[1] each as a 4-byte LITTLE-ENDIAN int32 = (long)(value*fp + 0.5) (bytes 8-11, 12-15,
      LSB first); then for i>=2: predicted = ints[1] + (ints[1]-ints[0]) on the QUANTIZED ints,
      diff = (int)(quant[i] - predicted), encoded via encodeInt's 4-bit half-byte scheme starting at byte 16,
      two half-bytes packed per byte, trailing odd half-byte flushed as (hb<<4). EncodeLinear(double[]) overload
      computes fp via OptimalLinearFixedPoint internally. (NOTE: values are 4-byte int32, NOT 5-byte.)
    - encodeInt/decodeInt: the canonical half-byte (nibble) scheme — head nibble encodes leading-zero count
      (0..8) or, for the 0xf0000000 case, leading-ones count + 8; remaining nibbles carry the value low-to-high.
      Port the bit loops EXACTLY from the reference (mask 0xf0000000, the init==0 / init==mask / else branches).
    - DecodeLinear(byte[]) reconstructs the array, mirroring the reference (read BE-double fp; first two as 4-byte
      LE int32 / fp; then extrapolate quantized ints and add decoded diff, divide by fp). dataSize==8 -> empty;
      dataSize<8 -> throw; dataSize==12 -> 1 value. Round-trip max|Δ| <= 0.5/fp.
    - Edge cases: empty array -> 8-byte (fp-only) output and decode -> empty; single value (12 bytes); two values
      (16 bytes, no residuals); ascending m/z slices of length 1..N.
    - EXACT VERIFICATION VECTORS (all MUST pass, byte-for-byte where stated):
      (V1) OptimalLinearFixedPoint([1.0,2.0,3.0]) == 1073741823 (== floor(0x7FFFFFFF / 2)).
      (V2) data=[100.0,100.5,101.0,101.5], fp=21367996 -> the canonical ms-numpress encode bytes; the first 8 bytes
           are BitConverter.DoubleToInt64Bits(21367996.0) in BIG-ENDIAN order (0x41 0x74 0x60 0xCB 0xC0 0x00 0x00 0x00);
           decode(encode) is exact.
      (V3) Reference row-0 fixed point: read mz_numpress_linear_bytes row 0 from refs/mzPeak/small.numpress.mzpeak,
           the first 8 bytes decoded as a BE double == 10599266.0; DecodeLinear of that row succeeds and its decoded
           m/z (after caller anchor-alignment, Task 2/4) is within 0.5/10599266 of the row's mz_chunk_start anchor.
      (V4) BYTE-IDENTITY at a shared fp, asserted TWICE: our EncodeLinear(data, fp) bytes ==
           (a) the known ms-numpress reference test-vector bytes for that data+fp, AND
           (b) pynumpress.encode_linear(data, fp) bytes. This is byte-identity, NOT merely decode-within-bound.
    - Cross-check vs pynumpress (python3.11, Ignore if absent): in addition to V4 byte-identity, assert
      pynumpress.decode_linear(our-C#-bytes) is within 0.5/fp, and OptimalLinearFixedPoint matches
      pynumpress.optimal_linear_fixed_point on real m/z slices.
    - phantom-leading-value: anchor decode to chunk start/end is the CALLER's concern (Task 2/4 test); the codec
      returns the raw MSNumpress decode. Document the artifact in the codec header note (no harness/phase wording).
  </behavior>
  <action>
